COMPOSITION WRITING
A composition is a piece of creative writing aimed at testing the candidate’s ability to
communicate using the language as a tool. A Candidate is expected to have sufficient command
of English in spoken and written forms to enable them to communicate well. The skill of writing
is one of the four skills of language taught in primary school. Learners are therefore taught to
relay and communicate information, ideas, feelings and opinion for leaders to communicate
according and confidently in writing; they ought to master basic writing skills
CHARACTERISTICS OF A GOOD COMPOSITION
The learner should have a combination of various writing skills that the candidate should have
accuracy, fluency and creativity i.e. originality and imagination
A composition should also have legible and neat hand writing.
The characteristics include:
a. Legible handwriting (clear and clean handwriting)
b. Vocabulary(choice of words)
c. Length
d. Fluency (the flow)
e. Creativity (originality and imagination)
f. Accuracy (correct English language)
Legible handwriting (clear and clean)
Handwriting is a mechanical skill that involves the formation of letters and words on paper using
the hand rather than trying or printing. A candidate must ensure that a composition is neatly
written in the most attractive and appealing handwriting. There should be good spacing of words
and sentences. The paragraph should be distinct. Poor handwriting creates a bad impression in
the mind of the marker however rich and entertaining the story may be.
Shaping of letters in confusing manner is a major problem facing English learners. This is
because of the inability to write clearly or careless stroke when forming letter. Letters which are
similar in shape e.g. U and V should be written clearly to avoid adding unnecessary “beauty
marks” to any letter because other people will not recognize them.
Letters with ascending (rising) stroke e.g. b, d, f, h, k, l & t should be written and shaped
clearly and elaborately. Similarly those with descending (falling) strokes e.g. g, j, p, q & y
should also come out clearly in addition letter which are of medium height that is those that can
never be the same height as those with either ascenders and descenders such as a, c, e, j, m, n, o,
r, s,u, v, w, x & z must also be taken .

Vocabulary (choice of words)
The writer should use the appropriate words that suit the theme and occasion. A good
composition should therefore have: - twin words, similes, idiomatic, expression, phrasal verbs,
proverbs, sound and dramatic expression. Words whose meaning are not fully understood must
be avoid it does not matter the number of times you send reader to the dictionary but just careful
choice and use of the intended words for the intended.
Length
A short story written in continuous form gives a bad impression to the maker. It reflects
inadequacy and language bankruptcy. The length of the composition should be three quarter ¾ of
writing surface i.e. At least two pages. However a composition that goes beyond three pages tend
to bore the examiner and in most cases the writer is likely to make unnecessary repetition
Fluency (the flow)
Fluency includes a coherent and consistent flow of information and ideas. It entails correct word,
sentence constructing, and logical sequence of ideas and good connection of paragraph.
A good writer will always carry the reader through his or her composition smoothly .This can
only be achieved if the paragraph are well linked and connected with the ideas logically and
systematically arranged. There should be no mixing up of points and jerky presentation. This
would automatically subject the ready to a “smooth ride.” It captures the reader’s attention. A
good writer should develop the story in the most attractive and appealing. When you begin to
write, think of how it would develop and end.
Creativity (originality and imagination)
Creativity here refers to the candidate’s ability to think, imagine and come up with original ideas
which develop a given a topic or the theme.
The writer must try to think out what to say and how to say it. A candidate should ensure that a
composition should contain writer’s own ideas which are original in the scene. They are not
memorized or pre learned extracts from different stories. Creativity ensures that a composition is
unique to the reader (examiner).
How to organize composition writing
Study the topic sentence (title) before writing. Title has three parts .The introduction, the body
and the conclusion.
Graphic organizer
This is a tool that helps writers to put information in an order before the start of draft.
a) Get the audience attention at the beginning and keeps throughout the story
b) The writer should tell the events in order they happen i.e. chronological order
The writer should include the details to make the story and character more real
and authentic.
c) The writer includes information about whom or what the story is about and when
and where it takes place.
Introduction
1. Lead – get the reader’s attention by writing down a captivating sentence. Example
“The long awaited day finally dawn into the limelight.”
2. Related statement- moves closer to the main idea in the paragraph. Example “The
villagers’ hustle and bustle to make both ends meet.”
3. Transitional statement- the main ideas of composition. The writer should break the
topic sentence. Example “The wedding ceremony was crowned with eye-catching,
fascinating and appealing decorations of different colours.”
In the introduction the writer should
1. Narrate the events in order they happen (chronologically)
2. Include details to make the story and the characters more real
3. Get readers attention at the beginning and keep it throughout the story
4. Add signal words to show how the ideas are connected e.g. first, suddenly, also,
however. The writer should eye on the clock. Decide on how much time you will
spend on each part of the writing process and try to stick to the schedule
5. The story should flow sequentially and orderly. The writer should use clear and
interesting details to describe people and events.
Body
The body of the composition is where the writer explain, describe, proves and gives information
about the main idea (topic sentence)
A paragraph is a group of related sentences. Every sentence in a paragraph should be about the
same main idea. A good paragraph should start with the idea you want the reader to know. This
will become the topic sentence i.e. using the words like; and, also, too, often. The writer should
focus on the things the reader will want to know.
The body has three parts
a. First supporting detail- start main idea in the first paragraph.
b. Second supporting detail-explain the events in chronological order.
c. Third supporting detail-discuss the events lengthily and sequentially.
d. These support, explain and gives more information about main idea of
composition
Conclusion
A brief summary of main ideas- restate the main ideas of body paragraph in summary
Other related statement- wraps up the composition.
Closing statement- The composition in the concluding paragraph should be so interesting eye,
catching and exciting .It should leave the reader amused and elated. It should also sum up the
important ideas in the composition all related ideas would be contained in one idea ending with a
proverb relevant to the subject matter. I should be brilliant idea.
A guide to a good composition writing
1. Read and understand the topic sentence clearly and adequately. Underline the key
words to avoid irrelevance.
2. Win and strike reader’s interest and attention through careful flow of events.
3. Avoid starting your sentence with conjunction e.g. and, or
4. Let your story revolve around the topic sentence and show clearly your setting
5. Avoid run-on sentence. Avoid long sentences and paragraphs. Construct short and
well punctuated sentences.
6. Avoid abbreviation in your composition because there have no place in formal
writing e.g. can’t, shan’t.
7. Avoid unnecessary repetition of certain words instead use a variety of sentence
8. Use grammar learnt accurately that is, sentence structures, tense and spelling
9. Set the mood and tone of your story. These are sorrows, joy, sadness, excitement
and happiness. The main character experience in the story ensure the reader also
experience the same mood
10. Be exact and original in terms of ideas and expression. Add taste to your
compositionbyusingrelevantcolloquialexpression,similes,metaphors,proverbs,hyp
erbolic humour and figures of expression and figures of speech
11. Use direct speech where applicable because dialogue involve the presence of the
reader
12. Use suspense by creating tragic scenes conflict or subject of disagreement in the
story without being irrelevant
13. Over and above proof read your work a composition free of mistakes is a good
and interesting one.
Suspense building and maintenance
Being in suspense may mean being in wrong, uncertain, frightening, horrifying, anxious and
expectant mood. Composition requires a great deal of creativity and imagination of events (non
existing things or events (fictions)
Suspense can be created through different ways such as telling bit by bit without disclosing
immediately.
The writing should enrich the language with
a. Vivid description using adjective and adjectival phrases to describe object
b. Using adverbs to demonstrate how an action took place
c. Hyper exaggeration of size objects or manners of action
d. Proverbs to conclude and summarized the story be peculiar to surprise the reader
with event.
The art of surprise makes a composition more captivating and interesting.
Let the story flow in a realistic and simplistic way example-:
A sad beginning> a happy end
A happy beginning>sad end
Sad > happy >sad
Happy > sad >happy.
Time
The first five minutes
What to be done
- Read the instruction given carefully
- Understand the topic sentence
- Make an outline of ideas as they occur in
chronological order
- Organize the ideas in sequential manner
The next 25-30 minutes
- Begin to write the composition
- Make at least one and a half pages
- To be able to write well on the topic sentence
- Stick to the topic sentence from the start to
the finish
The last five minutes
-Revise and proof read the composition time and
again
-Correct any error on tenses, spelling, grammar,
sentence pattern and paragraph-
Time budget and management
THE EYE-CATCHING EXPRESSIONS, MEANING AND USAGE
 She jumped up and down in a transport of joy.
 Meaning
 He brimmed with happiness and joy
Example: When chebet realized that she was the winner in KCPE results, she became elated
and excited. She jumped and up down in transport of joy.
 He disappeared like a racing driver
Meaning
To get lost into thin air
Example: The thief snatched my purse at the corridor to my house. He gripped it tightly
and disappeared like a racing driver into the forest.
 He made a little grim nod of satisfaction
Meaning
When he arrived at the grandmother’s house, she greeted her and made a little grim nod
of satisfaction. They greeted each other as joyfully as if they had not met for many years
 Life is too short for hurrying
Meaning
A person should not rush in dealing with anything.
Example: The teacher advised the boys not to get involved in worldly pleasures. He warned
them not to rush into dubious deals as the saying goes life is too short for hurrying.
 He bathed in a cold pool of frightened sweat
Meaning
He became scared and astonished
Tom was totally scared and surprised when his teacher announced the results.
He bathed in a cold pool of frightened sweat.
 A spasm of pain gripped his stomach
Meaning
Agonizing knots of pain took the better of him
Example: When George found his girl kidnapped on her way to the posho mill, he
encountered a spasm of pain gripped his stomach. Agonizing knots of pain gripped him
 He worked with frantic haste
Meaning
He moved hurriedly
Example: When he found the news at the notice board, he looked at the list in a frantic haste.
It was another such spectacular gesture to him.
 The institution degenerated into a noisy arena.
Meaning
